The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, August 18, 2004 				 Global Trust set to exit bourses 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, Aug. 17: Global Trust Bank will finally bid adieu to the stock exchanges and its shareholders in a quiet manner after a short but blistering stint on the bourses.																								The Global Trust scrip will be suspended and will not be available for trading from August 27, Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) said.																								The BSE and National Stock Exchange (NSE) have fixed the record date by the company as August 31.																								The GTB share became infamous after its price was allegedly rigged during the height of Ketan Parekhs bull run. The scrip traded at around Rs 2.15 and touched an intra-day high of Rs 2.75 before scraping the bottom at Rs 2.03. The share finally closed at Rs 2.31 with 12.46 lakh shares traded on the BSE.																								On Monday, Oriental Bank of Commerce  the blue chip bank which took over the beleaguered bank  indicated that the shareholders of Global Trust will have to wait for 12 years to get some sort of compensation.																								The GTB shareholders have been promised a residual value for their shares, while some want a more active role in asset valuation.																								The trades done in Global Trust stock on August 26 will be settled on August 30. If there is any shortage in delivery, it shall be closed on August 30, according to the procedure in place, BSE said.																								The members will be required to credit the securities received in payout of the above settlement in beneficiary accounts of their clients latest on August 31, the exchange added.																								Meanwhile, Oriental Bank has decided to appoint a global consultant to restructure and integrate GTB with itself within six months.																								We will soon hire an international consultant to sort out five important aspects of obc-gtb merger, OBC chairman B. D. Narang said.
